Record<K, T>

`Record<K, T>` constructs an object type with keys of type `K` and values of type `T`.

### Basic Usage

```typescript
type PageNames = "home" | "about" | "contact";

const pages: Record<PageNames, { title: string; url: string }> = {
  home: { title: "Home", url: "/" },
  about: { title: "About", url: "/about" },
  contact: { title: "Contact", url: "/contact" }
};
```

### Simple Key-Value Map

```typescript
const scores: Record<string, number> = {
  Alice: 95,
  Bob: 87,
  Charlie: 92
};

const config: Record<string, string | number | boolean> = {
  host: "localhost",
  port: 3000,
  secure: true
};
```

### How Record Works

```typescript
type Record<K extends keyof any, T> = {
  [P in K]: T;
};
```

### Enum Mapping Pattern

```typescript
enum Status {
  Active = "ACTIVE",
  Inactive = "INACTIVE",
  Pending = "PENDING"
}

const statusLabels: Record<Status, string> = {
  [Status.Active]: "User is active",
  [Status.Inactive]: "User is inactive",
  [Status.Pending]: "User is pending approval"
};

console.log(statusLabels[Status.Active]); // "User is active"
```

### Record with Complex Values

```typescript
type UserRole = "admin" | "editor" | "viewer";

interface RolePermissions {
  canCreate: boolean;
  canRead: boolean;
  canUpdate: boolean;
  canDelete: boolean;
}

const rolePermissions: Record<UserRole, RolePermissions> = {
  admin: { canCreate: true, canRead: true, canUpdate: true, canDelete: true },
  editor: { canCreate: true, canRead: true, canUpdate: true, canDelete: false },
  viewer: { canCreate: false, canRead: true, canUpdate: false, canDelete: false }
};
```

> **Key Point:** `Record` is ideal for typed dictionaries and mapping enums to associated data.

codeExample:
// HTTP header map
type HttpHeaders = Record<string, string>;

const headers: HttpHeaders = {
  "Content-Type": "application/json",
  "Authorization": "Bearer token123"
};

// Event handler registry
type EventName = "click" | "hover" | "focus" | "blur";
type EventHandler = (event: Event) => void;

const handlers: Record<EventName, EventHandler[]> = {
  click: [],
  hover: [],
  focus: [],
  blur: []
};

// State machine
type State = "idle" | "loading" | "success" | "error";
const stateMessages: Record<State, string> = {
  idle: "Waiting for input",
  loading: "Processing...",
  success: "Operation completed",
  error: "An error occurred"
};
